segments.text: Where would you eat?
Our favorite places, I guess, were, there were about three.
There was a, what was it called down at the, they called it at the Triangle.
There was a drive-in kind of restaurant down there.
We used to go down there quite a bit.
I forget the name of it.
There was a place that served huge cheap steaks and catfish out there on the Brazos River near the air base.
We'd go across to North Gate, and I forget the name of the restaurant where they served those greasy hamburgers.
Was Colonel Ed's Hard Liquor still going?
Not that I remember.
Down in Welborn?
A little earlier, that was a place to go get beer.
I don't remember that.
Was Whiskey Bridge a place where people went in your era?
Go straight toward Snook and immediately across the river could buy whiskey?
Never remember that.
Maybe they did.
I didn't.
Was beer available?
during your era in Brazos County?
You know, I guess I never drank any beer.
Never had the money to drink it.
I mean, when we went on a beer bus and they'd have a keg, I'd drink it because it was free.
Do you remember many times an Aggie being brought back to the campus pretty well drunk?
Did that happen very often?
Oh, it happened, but not very often.

of laugh about it take him in the shower and dump him in there did anybody in your memory get caught on an inspection having something illegal in their room never remember that at all but there were some people probably that had some some alcohol hidden i guess but i don't ever recall it happening um back to uh to athletics what are some of your favorite athletic memories of that era
The first Texas game when Buddy Schaefer, who preceded me at Austin High School, played football here, caught the winning pass in 51 against Texas.
That was Bob Smith's senior year.
Bob got, what's his name, gave him the four-inch shiver on the kickoff, Kyle Field, and put him out for the game.
We still won.
We beat Oklahoma that year, I think it was.
When Brian beat Texas, I guess, in Austin and sent Ed Price packing, who was the coach over there.
That was in 56, I guess, when I was in graduate school.
We didn't have, obviously, very good football teams, but it was always exciting.
And how were the athletes, as far as you knew, how were they treated?
They weren't treated hardly any different.
They were over at the companion building at Hart Hall, which was the same structure as Walton.
And I, because Dolla Hyde lived over there.
And I went over there, and we had a few of them that were married that lived in those married Quonset hut things down on South Gate, but most of them lived there in Hart.
As far as you knew, did they take the same courses that others took?
Were there any Crip courses just for athletes?
I think they took the same courses, as far as I know, that the other students in their discipline took.
That's what I mean.
Now, they might have taken Ag-Eco, but they took whatever.
Did you by chance know Bobby Drake Keith?
We know Keith real well.
See, he got a double major in petroleum engineering and geology in four years.
Gene Stallings got his degree in four years.
They got there about the time Gene was a freshman.
He and Drake were there when Bryant got there, one year.
That's right.
They got out in 57.
I think you're right.
So they got there in 53.
I believe so.
In your day, what did the typical Aggie student think about Yale leaders?
Was it a big deal to be a Yale leader?
I think so, yeah.
I think that was one of the more important positions on the campus.
I don't think anybody thought too much about class president or anything like that.
What was the highest prestige student position?
Corps commander?
Yeah, by far.
Was there even a student body president then?
Yes, there was.
Oh, there was?
Okay.
And class president, but that didn't matter much, did it?
I mean, if we had one, I didn't know who he was.
Was there much attention to student government?
You know, for those that were kind of involved in it, I'm sure there was.
But the body was the Corps.
The Corps commander was more important than the rest of it.
And I think there was the first stirrings maybe of, well there's something more to Texas A&M than the Corps.
There was some people, I'm trying to remember the name of that guy in our class who was, ended up as editor of the battalion.
And he kind of stirred some things up.
That's not at all unusual for student editors.
Were there any national or international events during your student days that you remember where you were when you heard the news?
I can't think of any during that time.
The first thing was after I left.

Because like I had just, the Kennedy assassination, I had just finished an 11 to 12 o'clock class in Nagel and I went into the office to get one of my friends and I said, come on, let's hurry to the MSC and beat the crowd.
I said, you can listen to the radio later.
And he said, listen.
And the first words I heard were Walter Cronkite saying, I've just been handed a bulletin.
President Kennedy is dead.
And then for the folks a little older than you and I, many of them when they heard the Pearl Harbor news were at Guyon Hall for the matinee and they interrupted it.
And they went running back to their dorm, and all of them said immediately we knew.
They were going.
They were going.
All right, now let's see.
When you were there, Korea was over.
Over.
I was between the two wars, so to speak.
We had to go in.
And I had, I was in the Air Force.
You had to pass the Air Force fiscal.
And a lot of my classmates, like George G. Singh, couldn't pass it, the flight fiscal.
So that weeded out on the Air Force side.
In fact, that was a big controversy, kind of, because so many of them had completed two years at A&M.
And then the Air Force, because they had that terrible surplus of pilots that they'd recalled for the Korean War and didn't want to really bust them out a second time.
They'd taken them out of a career.
So they ended up with too many people, and they were trying to get rid of
new people coming in, they had a budget problem.
So the students like George said, look, I've completed two years here, now you tell me that I can't stay here, it's a military school, but I can't stay.
So I want to transfer to the Army side, move over to the Army.
And the Army had a budget problem, and they wouldn't let them move over there, and that caused some hard feelings.
Did you Air Force ROTC members think that y'all were a little smarter than the Army?
Did y'all think the Air Force a little more?
Oh, well, you know, that went on forever.
That's right.
You know, why walk to where you're going when you can ride?
Were there any competitions?
I don't know how we didn't get killed.
Down in those steam tunnels?
How long before you learned about steam tunnels?
Well, there weren't steam tunnels until we moved over that I knew of until we got to what was called the new area when I was a sophomore.
And, you know, are you sophomores going to let those guys, those ground pounders over there get away with this?
So out we'd go down the steam tunnels, taking the caps off the toilets in the middle of the night, putting those bombs over there.
Oh, I mean.
How far?
As far as you know, how far did the steam tunnels extend on the campus?
I don't know.
It was always pitch black when I was in them, so I never... And in terms of dimension, the steam tunnel was about how big?
Six feet, something like that.
Six feet wide, maybe seven feet.
And were they bricked or were they sealed?
Well, they were sealed.
I mean, I guess they were bricked.
And what lines ran in them?
Well, the steam lines for the radiators in all of our rooms, and I assume the telephone and whatever else.
I guess it was a utility tunnel.
All the utility.
And where, say, from your dorm, where was the easiest place to enter the steam tunnel?
Where did you get in?
I think it was out there behind the dorm.
Over in the new dorm area?
Yeah.
And wasn't it locked?
No.
There was a ladder going down there.
Okay.
You know, it's amazing what you forget.
Then you go, you knew how to get there.
Somebody showed you how to get over to the other side.
Then you come out.
Because I think they ran literally almost all over the campus.

I'm sure they did, because when you mention that, I remember the steam tunnel that was between the old Y and the new, they built a brand new administration building where Harrington moved into, there across from the drill field, that little street.
Now, do you remember anybody ever getting hurt in the steam tunnel?
Fallen.
missing the ladder and going whomp in the bottom, breaking their arm.
Now, you did carry a flashlight, didn't you?
Oh, yeah.
Okay.
Okay.
I mean... One of my classmates in electrical engineering was Joe Bickley, who graduated from El Paso High.
The Bickleys were big cotton farmers up in Canyon Tia.
And that first, very first day, we were sitting in that class, and I think it was...
he wasn't a Dr. Rose, Norman Rose, I think, right?
Had each one of us tell where we were from.
And when he got to Joe, Joe didn't say El Paso, of course, Canyon T was up.
He says, oh, I know what it was.
He didn't ask us to say it.
He had the list of us and where we were from.
And he gets to Joe and he says, Mr. Bickley from Canoodle, Texas,
And Joe and I look at each other, of course, those days you didn't laugh or anything, and he says, sir, he says, that's Caatillo.
Caatillo.
Oh, okay.
So a little later, somebody asked, it wasn't Rose, but somebody said, y'all still have Indians out there?
Joe and I looked at each other and said, man, we haven't gone east, but they sure haven't gone west.
Mm-hmm.
At A&M, in that era, what was the, what were the events or traditions or whatever that pulled everybody together so well?
Well, I think it was, as I say, the core and everything that it embodied, from let's call it the metal hazing,
from the strict regimen that was imposed from 6 a.m. in the morning to whatever it was, we all endured it.
I thought about this a lot in relation to what I've done subsequently.
I think A&M turns out some of the best people in the world because of that regimen.
In many respects, we're very pragmatic, but we never quit.
That's one thing, we never, ever quit.
We may not turn out as many artists or people of that type.
What we do is, that's why so many presidents of oil companies, they're pragmatic, they're hardworking.
I don't guess we've turned out a lot of politicians, Perry and Sharp, but for the most part,
As a politician, I think we had a very, very good ethical.
You didn't lie, you didn't steal, and you didn't cheat, period.
And you went home if you did.
And that was ingrained.
What were the events that contributed most to, at A&M, that contributed most to those attitudes?
Well, as I say, the Corps.
But what else?
I think the fact that A&M was isolated had a lot to do with it because we didn't get exposure to a lot of things that other students got exposed to, good or bad, it molded our character.
I think the faculty had a lot to do with it.
I think we had a very conservative faculty.
But things like Yale practice and games.
Yale practice, final review, core trips.
You took care of each other.
Silver taps?
Silver taps.
Do you remember when you first went to a silver tap?
My freshman year.
Hadn't been there probably in October until somebody got killed in an automobile accident.
What was your feeling?
I didn't know at that time whoever it was.
And in fact, it wasn't a freshman.
It was somebody else, I recall.
But it was a tremendously moving experience.
I had never been involved in anything like that.
Did everybody take it seriously?
Oh, yes.
And I think as a freshman, if I recall, I said, in the middle of the night, I'm getting drug out to go to this thing in the world.
And then after that you realized that was part of this bonding.
And a lot of people don't understand that.
And I understand that too.
Final review.
I thought the Ross Volunteers did a lot of that.
I thought that building the bonfire did a lot of that.
Just having to march to every meal did a lot of that.
So after your sophomore year, you came back home, worked.
What about after, when did you go to summer camp the first time?
Well, we went between our junior and senior years.
So at the end of my junior year, I went out to summer camp.
Where?
March Air Force Base.
Joe Walker, who was head of Centex, was in my class.
He and Dale Fisher, I don't know where Dale is, but Joe and I stay in contact.
And the three of us, Joe picked up one of these cars where you drive.
In those days they may still do it.
They want a car moved from here to there.
And he got one in Dallas, came out here and picked Dale and I up and we went this March.
And how did you Aggies, how did summer, that summer camp go?
and we had a blast.
Did you all think you were well prepared?
Oh yeah, yeah.
Did any of the others look with any kind of special way upon you Aggies?
I think they kind of said, you know, you're taking this military a little too far.
And did that summer camp experience have any effect on you the next year?
Well, then I came back home and got married.
Okay.
But I always thought the summer camp was a great experience.
And it helped me, I thought, the three years that I was in the Air Force.
Right, so then you and your wife moved to Bryan College Station.
We moved.
And where did you find a place to live?
Well, old man Lauderstein had a terrible, rickety, old two-story house that he converted into four apartments there at Northgate.
It's been torn down.
It's about two blocks.
Remember what the rent was?
I think it was $30 a month.
And what kind of furniture did y'all take?
This was furnished.
It was the worst stuff you ever seen.
And I had a deal with him that he had three or four right there.
And I had a deal that I'd keep them repaired.
And he paid me 50 cents an hour.
And they all set up on whatever.
And we had a freeze.
And the pipes froze and broke.
And I'm in there that afternoon, right at freezing, mud on my back, putting in new sections of pipe.
But then the next year, while I was in graduate school, as I said, Chris Gronemann built those new little duplexes.
They're kind of dog-eared now.
I saw them a couple of months ago, but we moved over there.
And your wife got a job with Brian?
She originally, that was the first year of Gilmer Aiken.
And she originally couldn't get a job.
They didn't have any openings in Bryan.
So she got a job teaching in Snook.
And when we arrived about the 20th of August, they had sent a letter out to El Paso from Bryan saying, we've got an opening.
So we got the letter.
And she called SNCC and said, I'm not coming, and went to work with Brian.
And do you remember what her pay was?
Well, Gilmore-Aitken was $2,815 a year.
And I had a fellowship in graduate school over with the calculator lab, the thing that we did the utility studies for all the utilities up there.
What's his name?
What was the professor that ran that?
He talked.
Anyway, and so I had a fellowship, and we did load studies for all the utilities.
I got to know all of them in those days.
Before we quit, let's go back for you as a senior.
When did you get your senior ring?
You know, I don't wear either one because I played golf, and they started cutting my hands.
So about 20 years ago, I had to take them off, and I tried to give mine to my son.
But anyway, I got it.
You know, was it somewhere around Christmas maybe?
And how much did it cost, do you remember?
Where'd you get the money?
Well, you had to pay for it, I think, what, in May before you left school?
I think that's right.
Your junior year.
And was it, was it 50 bucks?
Something like that.
I think that's what it was.
How did you feel when you put it on?
Oh, I thought it was, I mean, I made it.
And I had saved the money.
I guess I, when I worked, I'd saved the money.
I'd paid for it.
You know, those things, I don't know, they've got to be worth a fortune.
I've got it in the lockbox.
Do you have any ring stories where something unusual happened or somebody saw it or you lost it?
I never lost it, but people would see it, especially if you were a couple times in New York City or in the Air Force.
Of course, there's a lot of Aggies, of course, who were in the military in those days.
Then you bought your senior boots?
I never had senior boots.
Of course, I was married, and I went in the day ducks.
Oh, so you didn't have to have senior boots.
Well, yeah, a lot of them did, but being married, and that was big money, I just didn't have any.
So you didn't go through final review your fourth year?
Oh, I did.
Oh, you did?
It was a day duck.
Oh, it was a day duck, okay.
How did you feel at final review and commencement?
I don't remember much about final review at that point.
Obviously, of course, being married, I said I made it.
I've done what I set out to do.
And I think that was a tremendous sense of accomplishment.
And I'll tell you this.
That day is the day you feel like you owe Texas A&M a tremendous debt of gratitude.
Why?

uh just because because you know there's a lot of people that had opportunity that didn't accept take it of course i knew i was going on to graduate school which made it a little different it wasn't like a final closure at that point do you remember who the commencement speaker was no i don't almost none of us do but what feeling did you have i remember my graduate school graduation more than i remember my
when you got that diploma?
I remember Harrington handing it to me.
And was it special to have your name called and your loved ones there?
That's right.
Let's quit at that point.
See, I think that's one of the very essential things that they must, must, must continue.
Yes, now they're having four commencements because there's so many names, but they're still calling every name and still shaking every hand.
that stage, and they look absolutely wonderful.
I guess, if you could see their face.
Sure.
Through the annuals, there was pictures.
Oh.
Sammy Kay, Tex Spinnicky, Ray Anthony, a bunch of them.
Oh, that's good.
Now, did you go to many of those dances?
No, I don't remember.
I never had the money.
I don't think I went to a dance.
For spending money, once you settled in, what did you do for money?
Well, I got $5 a week.
I had to buy haircuts, pay for any excess laundry, whatever.
But then I tried to work.
Where?
Well, because I was taking so many hours, I couldn't take, so I had to be a little, I sold Reader's Digest subscriptions.
I put up TV antennas, I told you about that.
I worked for old man Lauterstein repairing his apartments.

things that i could set my own hours and uh you went up to to denton about how often to visit that special young lady well about once a month you could go up there i could go i'm just amazed that i got thinking about that for a dollar or two i'd i'd hitchhike when you got up there they had an old clapboard house on campus with bunk bear cots in it for the aggies
You could stay there for, you got a towel and a bar of soap for 25 cents a night.

I could eat over in their dining hall, and then I, or we'd go out, she had put up half the money, my wife did, and we'd go to some, you know, fast food, whatever, the pig stand or whatever it was, and then you'd hitchhike back home.
Did you go to a dance up there quite often?
No, I may have gone to one up there.
Were there many Aggie-Tessie couples?
Yeah, lots of them.
The place was swarming with Aggies on the weekend.
And then when they came down to the campus.
They came on either the train or the bus.
They chartered a lot of buses.
And at the dances, how were all the young ladies treated at Aggie dances?
Oh, I think they were just treated magnificently.
I think Aggies treated their dates quite well.
I don't think they spent a lot of money on them.
And at A&M dances, was there heavy drinking?
Well, I don't think so, but I was never there.
I've not heard of any.
I don't think so.
I don't think anybody ever thought about doing something like that.
In your student era, did Aggies smoke?
Mm-hmm.
And what were they smoking?
Oh, I'm sure what everybody else, I guess, I didn't smoke.
But I'm sure they, Lucky Strikes and Camels and Old Gold and whatever.
Were cigars at all?
I think, no, not as a practice.
I think some guys would get a cigar and smoke it, but I don't think anybody that I knew could ever afford to buy a cigar.
Did you and your buddies even know the words related to drugs?
No, never heard of them.
And see, today's youngsters can't believe that.
Well, I don't think anybody.
Maybe there were somewhere else, maybe in big cities, but I mean, we never heard the word marijuana.
Did Aggies play cards sometimes, poker?
They played poker and moon.
Sometimes for money.
Yeah, a little, but I never saw any, very, very rarely.
Now, for you, how was it different to be a sophomore than it was to be a freshman?

Well, besides having the pressure of somebody on you all the time and having all the extracurricular stuff that they made you do, which made you relax a little more, you also realized, well, you were going to be there unless you flunked out for the duration.
And therefore, you were more at home with the university and the life of the university, which meant that you functioned better.
Now, you were in the same outfit as the sophomore?
Well, we had freshman outfits.
Oh, that's right.
And then you went to the new area, and it was squadron 14.
What was different about eating in Duncan compared to Sevesa?
The food was the same.
Not much, other than you weren't a freshman.
Do you remember some good dining hall pranks or jokes?
Well, I can't remember.
The only thing I can remember is stealing the pie.
You know, you didn't get cush when you were a freshman.
And I forget who it was, just went by the table and stole, there was always, you got two pies, I think it was, and took one of them.
I mean, you know, the upperclassmen just went crazy.
Oh you know the old the old stuff about you had to get up on sit on the back of your chair and the air raid drill and that kind of stuff but that had gone on for years.
Other than that I don't remember a lot about it.
Now did you were you ever subjected to cush questions?
Oh yeah yeah.
Now as a sophomore did you ever use the paddle on anybody?
I as I told you I had never other than when I was in the RVs
nor did I ever use it.
RVs.
We may have done this the other day, but I want to be sure.
Did you apply?
No, no.
We went through that.
I don't know how.
I don't know what the process, selection process was.
One day they called me over to some kind of meeting and said, you've been selected to be a member of the RVs.
Did you all have to buy your uniforms, or were they provided?
No, I think we bought our uniforms.
And how proud did you feel when you put it on?
Oh, I thought that was the greatest thing in the world.
And what were some of the ceremonies?
You remember RVs.
